results.notes:
Growing in moss, at least some of which appears to be sphagnum.
These were collected from an area of less than one square yard. A few were left in-situ, and a few were posed nearby.
Despite these all looking the same, and being collected in the same small area, there may actually be two distinct species. This suggestion is the result of having examined spores from two different fruit bodies (each pictured).
Spores:
1. from the largest cap visible. 7.5-8.5, nearly smooth, or perhaps with slightly wrinkled surfaces (when the sharp-focus is adjusted so the depth of field changes, slight textural differences are observed). Not calyptrate. Ellipsoid to sub-amygdaliform. Light rusty brown in KOH.
2. From one of the smaller caps. 10-12 × 6-7 (not including “wings”, see below), slightly verrucose (or perhaps smooth with some wrinkles). Distinctly calyptrate, with apical “wings”. Ellipsoid. Rick rusty brown in KOH.
If these are all the same species, then this example shows significant variability in spore morphology; if so, probably due to level of maturity of fruit body.

results.notes:
Two small basidiocarps fruiting in grass area right under Pinus taeda. Cap approximately 2-3.5 cm wide, whitish with bright, vibrant yellowish-gold fibrils, more prominent on the disc; gills free, pallid/white when young, becoming pinkish, then grayish and finally dark brown, bruising slightly where handled. Stipe flimsy, glabrous above small, flaring annulus, with yellowish/floccose material near enlarged, slightly bulbous, base, becoming hollow in age. All parts of the mushroom drying yellowish, with the cap drying to a very deep and vibrant gold color. Odor/taste non distinctive.

Spores smooth, with relatively thick wall, brown, ~ 5 – 6 × 3.5 – 4.5 (4.6) μm, (L’ = 5.42 μm; W’ = 3.99 μm; Q = 1.20 – 1.57; Q’ = 1.36; N = 19). Basidia 4 sterigmate, slightly to somewhat clavate, ~ 15 – 23 μm (Q’ = 2.79). Pleurocystidia absent (not found). Cheilocystidia septate, clavate, ~ 16-26 × 4 – 7 μm (L’ = 20.27 μm, W’ = 6.27, Q’ = 3.32). Pileipellis a cutis with septate elements, ~ 4-8 μm wide.

results.notes: Two small fruitings under oak, in very sandy soil. Macro – Pileus small, fragile slightly viscid/greasy (at least when wet), ~ 1.5-2.5 cm wide, mostly rimrose to slightly finely fibrillose, exhibiting a superficial, thin and brown layer, with appressed squamules, appearing to be falling off or disappearing (presumably in age); gills distant, pallid-grayish, faces becoming some what brownish in age, emarginate; stipe white, glabrous with very fine pruinose apex, ~ 0.5 cm wide by 2.5-3 cm in length, a small bulb at the stipe base present, entire stipe fragile, becoming dingy/brownish in age and subsequent to handling. Odor nondistinctive, did not taste. Micro – Spores pale amber in water and NH4OH, somewhat subheterodiametric in outline, nodulose with ~ 7 to 10 nodules, both obtuse and more acute in shape, ~ 7.0 – 9.5 × 5.5 – 7.5 μm, (L’ = 8.15 μm; W’ = 6.85 μm; Q = 1.11 – 1.28; Q’ = 1.19; Basidia observed with 4-sterigmata (~ 3-5 μm in length), generally cyclindrical to slightly clavate (infrequently subcapitate-shaped), ~ 25 – 32 × 8 – 11 μm, (L’ = 29.5 μm; W’ = 9.3 μm; Q = 2.9 – 3.64; Q’ = 2.9); Pleurocystidia present, common, long pyriform-ish, rounded apices, tapering downward to a small/slender pedicel, with and without crystals/encrustations at the apex, ~ 45 – 61 (72) x (15) 17 – 22 μm, (L’ = 56.13 μm; W’ = 18.47 μm; Q = 2.58 – 3.8; Q’ = 3.06); cheilocystidia abundant, very similar to pleurocystidia though generally more slender/shorter and also sometimes with a ventricose bottom half, with a more slender, constricted upper half, with/without apical crystalizations/encrustations, ~ (34) 40 – 50 × 11 – 15 (18) μm, (L’ = 43.3 μm; W’ = 12.8 μm; Q = 2.62- 4.55; Q’ = 3.5); lamellar trama consisting of parallel cell-like structures, cylindrical, septate (constricted at septa), generally around 50 × 20 μm, though very variable (up to 100 μm in length and as small as 3-4 μm in width). Pileipellis a cutis, elements septate.

results.notes:
Growing on small hardwood sticks.
These immature fruit bodies are only about one week old. (I have been checking the small area daily for over two weeks.) I removed the outer/upper covering (lid) on one, and as seen in the one photo, beneath this was a white surface. The white material turned out to a gelatinous substance within which the white peridioles were embedded (as seen in photos). This seems to point toward genus Nidularia… except the eggs are white and these don’t look like any photos of Nidularia that I have found. I searched for cords connecting the peridioles to the inside of the nest, but found none.
My guess is these are Crucibulum laeve that seem to exhibit atypical traits on account of being immature. The fruit bodies seen in this observation were collected only a few hours after heavy rainfall.
The MO observation obs 98997 seems to validate my belief that my present observation represents C. laeve. Note how the sectioned/unopened fruit body seen in 98997 shows the peridioles embedded in gel.
I left a few additional fruit bodies to mature.
Fourth photo down shows a post-mature fruit body (presumably the same species) attached to the same stick one of the featured entities. Probably a left-over from last year. There’s also a peridiole stuck to the old fruit body, from a previous fruiting.
